<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 6 — Categorical Propositions
  First full draft. Opening chapter of Part II.

  Scope:
  - The four standard form categorical propositions: A, E, I, O.
  - Two-circle Venn diagrams for each, using the standard 4-area
    numbering (1 = S only; 2 = S-and-P overlap; 3 = P only;
    4 = outside both).
  - Basic translation from English into standard form.
  - The (modern) square of opposition: just contradictories.
  - Existential commitment: modern interpretation only; universals
    interpreted as conditionals. Aristotelian interpretation is
    deferred to an appendix per PROJECT_PLAN.md §3.
  - Immediate inferences: conversion, obversion, contraposition,
    with the modern-interp validity table.
  - More complex translations: singular statements via identity,
    "only" and "none but," and other patterns.

  Voice: matter-of-fact, declarative, real-world / political
  examples where they land. Several translation examples are
  adapted from the lead author's Spring 2026 Exam 2 study guide.

  Diagrams: 2-circle Venn diagrams generated in TikZ. Each
  <image> includes a <description> with full alt text using the
  4-area convention so screen-reader users get an alternate
  encoding equivalent to the visual diagram.

  Notes for review:
  - Venn diagrams should continue to be checked visually after
    any geometry or rendering changes.
  - Mood and figure are deferred to Chapter 7 (syllogisms).
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-categorical-propositions">

  <title>Categorical Propositions</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-categorical-propositions-intro">
    <p>
      Part I gave us the conceptual frame for evaluating arguments:
      validity and soundness, strength and cogency, the recognition
      and reconstruction skills that let us put an argument into a
      form we can examine. Part II turns to procedure. We start
      with the oldest formal system in the Western tradition:
      <term>categorical logic</term>, which goes back to Aristotle
      and which still does real work for a particular class of
      everyday arguments.
    </p>
    <p>
      Categorical logic is the logic of arguments built from
      statements about <em>categories</em>: claims of the form
      <q>All parking apps are tiny tests of patience,</q> <q>No
      group projects are acts of divine mercy,</q> <q>Some
      vibe-coded tools are excellent programs,</q> and <q>Some
      emails marked urgent are not actual emergencies.</q> A
      surprising amount of ordinary reasoning has this shape —
      about voters, programs, defendants, species, students, and
      policies. Once we can put such reasoning into standard form,
      a small piece of geometric machinery (Venn diagrams) decides
      validity for us.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter is about the basic units: the four standard form
      categorical propositions. We'll learn what they are, how to
      translate ordinary English into them, the relations among
      them, and the inferences that move from one to another. The
      next chapter combines them into syllogisms and uses
      three-circle Venn diagrams to evaluate the syllogisms for
      validity.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-standard-form-propositions">
    <title>The Four Standard Form Categorical Propositions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A <term>categorical proposition</term> is a statement that
        relates two categories — a <term>subject term</term> S and a
        <term>predicate term</term> P — by claiming one of four
        things about them. The four are called A, E, I, and O. The
        letter names are traditional and useful because every later
        piece of categorical machinery refers back to them. The
        labels become familiar by translating and diagramming
        examples, not by treating them as isolated vocabulary.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-quantity-and-quality">
      <title>Quantity and quality</title>
      <p>
        Each categorical proposition has a <term>quantity</term> and
        a <term>quality</term>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Quantity</alert> is universal or particular. A
        <em>universal</em> proposition says something about every
        member of S. A <em>particular</em> proposition says
        something about at least one member of S.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Quality</alert> is affirmative or negative. An
        <em>affirmative</em> proposition says S members are P. A
        <em>negative</em> proposition says S members are not P.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two values for quantity, two for quality, gives four
        combinations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>A</alert> — universal affirmative: <q>All S are P.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><alert>E</alert> — universal negative: <q>No S are P.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><alert>I</alert> — particular affirmative: <q>Some S are P.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><alert>O</alert> — particular negative: <q>Some S are not P.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The letters supposedly come from medieval Latin: A and I
        from <em>affirmo</em> (I affirm), E and O from <em>nego</em>
        (I deny). I actually don't know if that's true, but the
        convention of using A, E, I, and O to refer to these
        standard form propositions is very old. Even older than I am.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-venn-numbering">
      <title>The four areas of a two-circle Venn diagram</title>
      <p>
        We will represent each categorical proposition with a
        two-circle Venn diagram. Two overlapping circles labeled S
        (left) and P (right) divide the universe into four areas.
        The standard numbering of these areas, used throughout this
        chapter and again when we describe diagrams in alt text:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>Area 1</alert>: inside S but outside P. (Things that are S and not P.)</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 2</alert>: inside both S and P. (Things that are both S and P.)</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 3</alert>: inside P but outside S. (Things that are P and not S.)</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 4</alert>: outside both circles. (Things that are neither S nor P.)</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Two conventions communicate the propositions:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Shading</alert> an area means that area is
            empty. There is nothing in that area.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            An <alert>X</alert> in an area means that area has at
            least one member. There is at least one thing there.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Shading is for universal propositions; X is for particular
        propositions. With those two conventions, the four standard
        form propositions get four characteristic diagrams.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-A-proposition">
      <title>The A proposition: All S are P</title>
      <p>
        The A proposition says every member of S is also a member of
        P. In Venn-diagram terms, that means there are no members of
        S outside P — area 1 is empty.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-A-proposition">
        <caption>The A proposition, <q>All S are P.</q> Area 1 is shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-A-proposition" width="55%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with the S circle on the
              left and the P circle on the right, overlapping in
              the middle. The standard numbering assigns area 1 to
              the part of S outside P, area 2 to the overlap of S
              and P, area 3 to the part of P outside S, and area 4
              to the universe outside both circles. In this
              diagram, area 1 is shaded, indicating that nothing
              that is S fails to also be P. Areas 2, 3, and 4 are
              unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-2) rectangle (3,2);
                \fill[white] \Pright;
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.7,1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (-1.3,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.3,1.7) {\small 4};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-E-proposition">
      <title>The E proposition: No S are P</title>
      <p>
        The E proposition says no member of S is also a member of
        P. In Venn-diagram terms: nothing is in both circles at
        once. Area 2 is empty.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-E-proposition">
        <caption>The E proposition, <q>No S are P.</q> Area 2 is shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-E-proposition" width="55%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with the S circle on the
              left and the P circle on the right, overlapping in
              the middle. Area 1 is the part of S outside P; area
              2 is the overlap of S and P; area 3 is the part of P
              outside S; area 4 is outside both circles. Area 2 is
              shaded, indicating that nothing is both S and P.
              Areas 1, 3, and 4 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \fill[gray!40] \Pright;
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.7,1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (-1.3,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.3,1.7) {\small 4};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-I-proposition">
      <title>The I proposition: Some S are P</title>
      <p>
        The I proposition says at least one S is also a P. In
        Venn-diagram terms: there is at least one thing in the
        overlap. Area 2 contains an X.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-I-proposition">
        <caption>The I proposition, <q>Some S are P.</q> An X appears in area 2.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-I-proposition" width="55%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with the S circle on the
              left and the P circle on the right, overlapping in
              the middle. Area 1 is the part of S outside P; area
              2 is the overlap of S and P; area 3 is the part of P
              outside S; area 4 is outside both circles. An X is
              placed in area 2, indicating that at least one thing
              is both S and P. No areas are shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.7,1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (-1.3,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0.3) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.3,1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (0,-0.1) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-O-proposition">
      <title>The O proposition: Some S are not P</title>
      <p>
        The O proposition says at least one S is not a P. In
        Venn-diagram terms: there is at least one thing in S that
        is outside P. Area 1 contains an X.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-O-proposition">
        <caption>The O proposition, <q>Some S are not P.</q> An X appears in area 1.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-O-proposition" width="55%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with the S circle on the
              left and the P circle on the right, overlapping in
              the middle. Area 1 is the part of S outside P; area
              2 is the overlap of S and P; area 3 is the part of P
              outside S; area 4 is outside both circles. An X is
              placed in area 1, indicating that at least one thing
              is S but not P. No areas are shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,0) circle (1.3)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.7,1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (-1.3,0.3) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.3,1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.1) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Four propositions, four diagrams. The pattern becomes
        familiar through use: A and E are universal (shading); I
        and O are particular (X). A and I are affirmative (the
        marked area is the overlap side, area 2); E shades area 2
        to deny it. O places an X in area 1 to affirm at least one
        S that is not a P. These four propositions, with these four
        diagrams, are the starter kit for everything that follows.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-basic-translation">
    <title>Basic Translation into Categorical Propositions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Real arguments are not written in standard form. To use
        categorical machinery on them, we have to <em>translate</em>
        ordinary English sentences into the A, E, I, or O form.
        Translation is a skill, not a procedure: there are common
        patterns, but judgment is required at the edges.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-translation-patterns">
      <title>Patterns and signal words</title>
      <p>
        A few signal words and phrases reliably indicate each form.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>A (universal affirmative).</alert> Indicators include
        <em>all</em>, <em>every</em>, <em>any</em>, <em>each</em>,
        and bare plurals interpreted universally (<q>kangaroos are
        marsupials</q> goes to <q>All kangaroos are marsupials</q>).
        A definite-article generic — <q>the platypus is a mammal</q>
        — is also typically A.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>E (universal negative).</alert> Indicators include
        <em>no</em>, <em>none</em>, <em>not any</em>, <em>nothing
        is</em>. <q>No spiders are insects</q> is canonically E.
        <q>There aren't any X who are Y</q> is also E.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>I (particular affirmative).</alert> Indicators include
        <em>some</em>, <em>a few</em>, <em>many</em>, <em>most</em>,
        <em>there are</em>. <q>Many voters are dissatisfied</q>
        translates to <q>Some voters are dissatisfied people.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>O (particular negative).</alert> Indicators include
        <em>some are not</em>, <em>not all</em>, <em>not every</em>.
        <q>Not all jerks are mean</q> translates to <q>Some jerks
        are not mean.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-translation-examples">
      <title>A small set of worked translations</title>
      <p>
        Each example below takes an English sentence and translates
        it into one of the four standard forms. The translations
        sometimes need a tiny bit of rephrasing to make the subject
        and predicate genuinely class terms.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-translation-set">
        <title>Translations into standard form</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>1.</alert> <q>No human being can swim across the Atlantic Ocean.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>No human beings are creatures that can swim across the Atlantic Ocean.</q> (E)</p>
          <p><alert>2.</alert> <q>Kangaroos are marsupials.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>All kangaroos are marsupials.</q> (A)</p>
          <p><alert>3.</alert> <q>Not all politicians are liars.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>Some politicians are not liars.</q> (O)</p>
          <p><alert>4.</alert> <q>Some Vikings practiced ritual human sacrifice.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>Some Vikings are people who practiced ritual human sacrifice.</q> (I)</p>
          <p><alert>5.</alert> <q>Spiders aren't insects.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>No spiders are insects.</q> (E)</p>
          <p><alert>6.</alert> <q>It's false that no college students voted for Trump.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>Some college students are people who voted for Trump.</q> (I)</p>
          <p><alert>7.</alert> <q>There aren't any Sanders supporters who are Republicans.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>No Sanders supporters are Republicans.</q> (E)</p>
          <p><alert>8.</alert> <q>Some people don't vote.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>Some people are not voters.</q> (O)</p>
          <p><alert>9.</alert> <q>Not all wizards demean goblins.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>Some wizards are not goblin demeaners.</q> (O)</p>
          <p><alert>10.</alert> <q>Some voters aren't sure how they'll vote in the 2026 midterms.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>Some voters are not people who are sure how they'll vote in the 2026 midterms.</q> (O)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Two of the trickiest translation moves — singular sentences
        like <q>Today is Monday</q> and <q>only</q> sentences like
        <q>Only Trump supporters are true Americans</q> — are
        deferred to <xref ref="sec-complex-translations"/>, where
        we have the additional tools to handle them cleanly.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-square-of-opposition">
    <title>The Square of Opposition</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The four propositions A, E, I, O are related to each other.
        Knowing one of them sometimes lets us infer the truth or
        falsity of others without further evidence. The diagram of
        these relations is called the <term>square of
        opposition</term>.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-modern-square">
      <title>The modern square: just contradictories</title>
      <p>
        The modern square keeps one relation: <term>contradiction</term>.
        Two propositions are contradictory when one is the exact
        denial of the other — they cannot both be true and they
        cannot both be false. There are exactly two pairs of
        contradictories among the four standard forms:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>A and O</alert> are contradictories. <q>All S are P</q> is the denial of <q>Some S are not P,</q> and vice versa.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>E and I</alert> are contradictories. <q>No S are P</q> is the denial of <q>Some S are P,</q> and vice versa.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In the medieval square, three more relations appeared:
        contraries (between A and E), subcontraries (between I and
        O), and subalternation (between A and I, and between E and
        O). The modern square drops these because each of them
        depends on the assumption that the subject term picks out
        at least one existing thing — an assumption we'll examine
        and let go of in <xref ref="sec-existential-commitment"/>.
        For now we keep only the relations that survive without
        that assumption, which is contradiction.
      </p>
      <p>
        This means that I and O propositions do not logically imply
        each other. From <q>Some S are P</q> it does not follow
        that <q>Some S are not P.</q> Maybe every S is a P. And
        from <q>Some S are not P</q> it does not follow that
        <q>Some S are P.</q> Maybe no S is a P. In ordinary
        conversation, though, the word <q>some</q> often suggests
        <q>some but not all.</q> If I say, <q>Some students passed
        the exam,</q> you may reasonably hear me as suggesting that
        some students did not pass. That suggestion is
        <term>pragmatic</term>: it comes from how the sentence is
        used in context. The logical content we are testing here is
        <term>semantic</term>: what the sentence strictly says. In
        categorical logic, <q>some</q> means <q>at least one.</q>
        It does not mean <q>at least one but not all.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-immediate-inference-by-contradiction">
      <title>Immediate inference by contradiction</title>
      <p>
        An <term>immediate inference</term> is an inference from
        one categorical proposition to another, with no premises in
        between. The contradictory relation gives us our first
        family of immediate inferences. Knowing the truth value of
        any A, E, I, or O proposition lets us read off the truth
        value of its contradictory immediately.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-immediate-by-contradiction">
        <title>Inferences via contradiction</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>From A to ~O.</alert> If <q>All voters are registered</q> is true, then <q>Some voters are not registered</q> is false. The symbol <q>~</q> is read <q>it is not the case that</q> or <q>it is false that.</q> So <q>~O</q> means <q>it is false that the O proposition is true.</q></p>
          <p><alert>From ~A to O.</alert> If <q>All voters are registered</q> is false, then <q>Some voters are not registered</q> is true.</p>
          <p><alert>From E to ~I.</alert> If <q>No senators voted against the bill</q> is true, then <q>Some senators voted against the bill</q> is false.</p>
          <p><alert>From ~E to I.</alert> If <q>No senators voted against the bill</q> is false, then <q>Some senators voted against the bill</q> is true.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Several translations from <xref ref="sec-basic-translation"/>
        used this move silently. <q>It's false that no college
        students voted for Trump</q> is the negation of an E
        proposition, so by contradiction it is equivalent to the
        corresponding I proposition — <q>some college students are
        people who voted for Trump.</q> The translation is just
        the inference made explicit. <q>Not all politicians are
        liars</q> is the negation of an A proposition, equivalent
        by contradiction to the corresponding O proposition —
        <q>some politicians are not liars.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-existential-commitment">
    <title>Existential Commitment</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A categorical proposition is a claim about a subject class.
        Does asserting <q>All S are P</q> commit us to the existence
        of at least one S? It seems like it should — if no S exist,
        what does the claim even say?
      </p>
      <p>
        The answer turns out to depend on which interpretation of
        categorical logic we adopt. The traditional Aristotelian
        interpretation says yes: A and E propositions carry
        existential commitment, so <q>all unicorns are magical</q>
        would be false on that reading, because there are no
        unicorns. The modern interpretation says no: A and E are
        treated as conditional claims, and they can be true even
        when their subject class is empty. This book uses the
        modern interpretation throughout. The Aristotelian
        interpretation is treated in
        <xref ref="appendix-aristotelian-categorical"/> for
        adopters who want to teach it.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-modern-existential">
      <title>The modern interpretation</title>
      <p>
        On the modern interpretation, the four forms commit us to
        existence as follows:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>A (All S are P).</alert> No existential commitment. Equivalent to the conditional: <em>for any thing, if it is an S, then it is a P</em>. If there are no Ss at all, the conditional is vacuously true.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>E (No S are P).</alert> No existential commitment. Equivalent to: <em>for any thing, if it is an S, then it is not a P</em>. Again, if there are no Ss, vacuously true.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>I (Some S are P).</alert> Existential commitment. Says <em>there is at least one thing</em> that is both S and P. Cannot be true if there are no Ss.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>O (Some S are not P).</alert> Existential commitment. Says <em>there is at least one thing</em> that is S and not P. Cannot be true if there are no Ss.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In other words, the universals are conditional and so do
        not require their subject term to pick out anything. The
        particulars are existential and so do.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-empty-subjects">
      <title>What happens when the subject is empty</title>
      <p>
        On the modern interpretation, <q>All unicorns are magical
        beasts</q> comes out true, because there are no unicorns
        and the conditional <em>if anything is a unicorn, then it
        is a magical beast</em> is vacuously satisfied. The same
        goes for <q>No unicorns are felines</q> — vacuously true.
        But <q>Some unicorns are magical</q> and <q>Some unicorns
        are not magical</q> are both false, because each requires
        at least one actual unicorn.
      </p>
      <p>
        This may feel counterintuitive on first encounter. The
        intuition that <q>all unicorns are magical</q> is somehow
        not quite a real claim is exactly the intuition the
        Aristotelian interpretation tries to capture. The modern
        interpretation gains something in exchange: it gives us a
        clean, simple system that aligns with how universals work
        in mathematics, science, and modern logic. We accept the
        small initial weirdness for the larger payoff.
      </p>
      <p>
        Several inferences that are valid on the Aristotelian
        interpretation become invalid on the modern one — most
        notably the inference from a universal to its corresponding
        particular (<q>All S are P; therefore some S are P</q> is
        valid on the Aristotelian view but invalid on the modern
        view, because the universal does not entail the existence
        of any S). This is why the modern square keeps only
        contradiction. We will see the consequences for syllogisms
        in <xref ref="ch-categorical-syllogisms"/> when certain
        traditionally-valid forms come out invalid in the modern
        system.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-other-immediate-inferences">
    <title>Conversion, Obversion, and Contraposition</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Three additional operations on a categorical proposition
        sometimes produce a logically equivalent proposition and
        sometimes produce a non-equivalent one. Knowing which
        operation is valid for which form is the second family of
        immediate inferences.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-conversion">
      <title>Conversion</title>
      <p>
        <term>Conversion</term> swaps the subject and predicate
        terms.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>The converse of <q>All S are P</q> is <q>All P are S.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The converse of <q>No S are P</q> is <q>No P are S.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The converse of <q>Some S are P</q> is <q>Some P are S.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The converse of <q>Some S are not P</q> is <q>Some P are not S.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        On the modern interpretation, conversion is valid for E
        and I and invalid for A and O.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>E is convertible.</alert> <q>No senators are unanimous voters</q> is equivalent to <q>No unanimous voters are senators.</q> Negative universals work in either direction.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>I is convertible.</alert> <q>Some voters are independents</q> is equivalent to <q>Some independents are voters.</q> Particular affirmatives are symmetric.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>A is not convertible.</alert> <q>All cats are mammals</q> is true; <q>All mammals are cats</q> is false. The original and the converse are not equivalent.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>O is not convertible.</alert> <q>Some students are not residents</q> can be true while <q>Some residents are not students</q> is also true (or false) independently — the truth value of the converse does not follow from the truth value of the original.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-obversion">
      <title>Obversion</title>
      <p>
        <term>Obversion</term> changes the quality of the
        proposition (affirmative becomes negative or vice versa)
        and replaces the predicate term with its complement (<em>P</em>
        becomes <em>non-P</em>).
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>The obverse of <q>All S are P</q> is <q>No S are non-P.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The obverse of <q>No S are P</q> is <q>All S are non-P.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The obverse of <q>Some S are P</q> is <q>Some S are not non-P.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The obverse of <q>Some S are not P</q> is <q>Some S are non-P.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Obversion is valid for all four forms. Each proposition is
        equivalent to its obverse.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-obversion-uses">
        <title>Obversion in translation</title>
        <statement>
          <p><q>All crayons are non-toxic things</q> obverts to <q>No crayons are toxic things,</q> and the two are logically equivalent.</p>
          <p><q>Some smart people are dupes of TikTok culture</q> obverts to <q>Some smart people are not non-dupes-of-TikTok-culture,</q> a clunkier but logically equivalent claim.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-contraposition">
      <title>Contraposition</title>
      <p>
        <term>Contraposition</term> replaces the subject term with
        the complement of the predicate term, and the predicate
        term with the complement of the subject term.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>The contrapositive of <q>All S are P</q> is <q>All non-P are non-S.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The contrapositive of <q>No S are P</q> is <q>No non-P are non-S.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The contrapositive of <q>Some S are P</q> is <q>Some non-P are non-S.</q></p></li>
        <li><p>The contrapositive of <q>Some S are not P</q> is <q>Some non-P are not non-S.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        On the modern interpretation, contraposition is valid for A
        and O and invalid for E and I.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>A is contrapositive.</alert> <q>All citizens are voters</q> is equivalent to <q>All non-voters are non-citizens.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><alert>O is contrapositive.</alert> <q>Some students are not seniors</q> is equivalent to <q>Some non-seniors are not non-students.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><alert>E is not contrapositive.</alert> <q>No school board members are ridiculous clowns</q> is not equivalent to <q>No non-ridiculous-clowns are non-school-board-members.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><alert>I is not contrapositive.</alert> <q>Some voters are independents</q> is not equivalent to <q>Some non-independents are non-voters.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Use the validity table at the end of this section while you
        practice. Conversion: E and I valid, A and O invalid.
        Obversion: all four valid. Contraposition: A and O valid,
        E and I invalid. The pattern becomes practically useful
        when you apply it to examples.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-validity-table">
      <title>The validity table for immediate inferences</title>
      <p>
        Summary, on the modern interpretation:
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Conversion</alert> — valid for E and I; invalid for A and O.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Obversion</alert> — valid for all four (A, E, I, O).
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Contraposition</alert> — valid for A and O; invalid for E and I.
      </p>
      <p>
        Combining these with contradiction (from
        <xref ref="sec-square-of-opposition"/>) gives us a small
        toolkit. Many real arguments depend on chaining several of
        these moves; the toolkit is what makes that chaining
        precise.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-complex-translations">
    <title>More Complex Translations</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The straightforward translation patterns from
        <xref ref="sec-basic-translation"/> handle most ordinary
        sentences. A few patterns require a bit more work, and in
        particular two patterns are common enough that we treat
        them in detail: <em>singular statements</em> and the
        <em>only</em> family.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-singular-and-identity">
      <title>Singular statements via identity</title>
      <p>
        A <term>singular statement</term> is a statement about a
        specific individual rather than about a category — for
        example, <q>Donald Trump is the 47th president of the
        United States.</q> Categorical logic is a logic of
        categories, but with a small trick we can fit singular
        statements into the framework. We turn the individual into
        a category — the category of things identical to that
        individual.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>Today is Monday</q> becomes <q>All days identical to
        today are Mondays.</q> The subject class is the category of
        days that are identical with today (a class with exactly
        one member, namely today itself); the predicate class is
        the category of Mondays. The translation is technically a
        universal A proposition; it works because the subject class
        has a single member.
      </p>
      <p>
        Identity statements work the same way but require care.
        Consider the sentence <q>Donald Trump is the 47th president
        of the United States.</q> One natural translation:
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>All people identical to Donald Trump are people
        identical to the 47th president of the United States.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        That captures one direction of the identity. But identity
        is symmetric — Trump <em>is</em> the 47th president if and
        only if the 47th president <em>is</em> Trump. To express
        the full identity claim in categorical form, we need
        <em>both</em> directions:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-identity-translation">
        <title>Translating an identity claim</title>
        <statement>
          <p><q>Donald Trump is the 47th president of the United States.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>All people identical to Donald Trump are people identical to the 47th president of the United States.</q> (A)</p>
          <p>→ AND <q>All people identical to the 47th president of the United States are people identical to Donald Trump.</q> (A)</p>
          <p>You need both directions to capture the identity claim.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The same holds for any identity claim: <q>The murder weapon
        was the candlestick</q>; <q>Aristotle is the author of the
        <em>Nicomachean Ethics</em></q>; <q>Twain is Clemens.</q>
        Each requires both directions in standard form.
      </p>
      <p>
        Singular non-identity statements (where the predicate is a
        general category rather than another individual) need only
        one direction. <q>Trump was nominated for a Nobel Peace
        Prize</q> becomes <q>All people identical to Trump are
        people nominated for a Nobel Peace Prize.</q> Just one A
        proposition; the predicate is a class, not a specific
        individual.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-only-and-none-but">
      <title>Only and none but</title>
      <p>
        The word <em>only</em> reverses the order of the subject
        and predicate in standard-form translation. This trips
        students up reliably, so it is worth taking slowly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider <q>Only Trump supporters are true Americans.</q>
        The natural reading: if you are a true American, then you
        are a Trump supporter. (The sentence does <em>not</em> say
        all Trump supporters are true Americans; it restricts true
        Americans to that group.) The standard-form translation:
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>All true Americans are Trump supporters.</q> (A)
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that the subject and predicate of the standard form
        are reversed from the surface order of the English. <q>Only
        X are Y</q> becomes <q>All Y are X.</q> The same goes for
        <q>None but</q>: <q>None but registered voters can vote</q>
        becomes <q>All voters are registered voters.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        Similar pairs:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-only-translations">
        <title>Translating <em>only</em></title>
        <statement>
          <p><q>Only planets support life.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>All life-supporting bodies are planets.</q> (A)</p>
          <p><q>Only true Americans are Trump supporters.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>All Trump supporters are true Americans.</q> (A)</p>
          <p><q>None but Sanders supporters supported Sanders.</q></p>
          <p>→ <q>All people who supported Sanders are Sanders supporters.</q> (A; trivially true)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A common mistake is to read <q>only X are Y</q> as <q>all X
        are Y.</q> They are different claims. <q>Only people with
        Virginia driver's licenses can vote in Virginia</q> says
        every voter has a Virginia license. It does <em>not</em>
        say everyone with a Virginia license votes (most of them
        don't, in any election cycle).
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-other-tricky-translations">
      <title>A few other tricky cases</title>
      <p>
        Some patterns need a small reframing to translate cleanly.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Adverbial sentences.</alert> <q>America became great
        again</q> isn't quite about a class of things by surface
        grammar, but rephrased as a categorical claim it becomes
        <q>All countries identical to America are countries that
        are great again.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Conditional-style imperatives.</alert> <q>America!
        Love it or leave it</q> is exhortation, not assertion, but
        if we read its propositional content, it claims something
        like <q>All those who do not love America are those who
        should leave America.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Negated existence.</alert> <q>It's false that no X
        are Y</q> is the denial of an E proposition, equivalent by
        contradiction to the corresponding I — <q>some X are Y.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Negated universality.</alert> <q>It's false that
        only X are Y</q> means there are some Ys who are not X — a
        denial of <q>All Y are X,</q> equivalent by contradiction
        to <q>Some Y are not X.</q> So <q>it's false that only
        Republican die-hards voted for Trump</q> becomes <q>Some
        Trump voters are not Republican die-hards.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        Translation rewards practice. The end-of-chapter exercises
        contain a wider variety of cases.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-categorical-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        We have the four standard form propositions, the basic
        translation patterns, the modern square of opposition, the
        existential-commitment story, and the validity table for
        conversion, obversion, and contraposition. This is the
        starter kit.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-categorical-pivot">
      <title>What's coming</title>
      <p>
        The next chapter combines categorical propositions into
        <term>syllogisms</term> — three-proposition arguments with
        two premises and a conclusion, all in standard form. Two
        evaluation methods will appear there: <em>Venn diagrams</em>
        for syllogisms (using three overlapping circles and the
        same shading and X conventions we used here, just with a
        third circle for the middle term), and <em>mood and
        figure</em> classification, which encodes a syllogism's
        structure in a short label like <q>AAA-1</q> or
        <q>EIO-2.</q> The Venn-diagram method is the primary
        technique. The mood-and-figure classification serves as an
        alternate encoding equivalent to the diagram for purposes
        of validity assessment, useful in particular for blind
        students for whom diagrams are not the natural medium.
      </p>
      <p>
        Once we can evaluate syllogisms, we will have answered the
        first formal question this book promised: <em>is this
        argument valid?</em> The answer will hold for any argument
        that fits the categorical-syllogism shape. Many real
        arguments do fit that shape. Many do not, and for them we
        will turn in Part III to sentential logic.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch6">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced categorical propositions and their
      two-circle Venn diagrams. The core ideas, section by section:
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>The Four Standard Form Categorical Propositions (§6.1).</alert>
      Categorical propositions relate a subject term S and a predicate
      term P. The four standard forms are A (<q>All S are P</q>), E
      (<q>No S are P</q>), I (<q>Some S are P</q>), and O (<q>Some S
      are not P</q>). Universal forms shade regions; particular forms
      place Xs.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Basic Translation into Categorical Propositions (§6.2).</alert>
      Ordinary English often has to be cleaned up before it fits the
      A/E/I/O forms. Translation requires identifying the subject and
      predicate classes, preserving the intended quantity and quality,
      and avoiding changes that alter the claim.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>The Square of Opposition (§6.3).</alert> On the modern
      interpretation, the square of opposition keeps contradiction as
      the load-bearing relation: A contradicts O, and E contradicts I.
      This gives valid immediate inferences from a proposition to the
      denial of its contradictory, and from the denial of a proposition
      to its contradictory. I and O do not logically imply each other,
      even though ordinary uses of <q>some</q> sometimes suggest
      <q>some but not all</q> pragmatically.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Existential Commitment (§6.4).</alert> This book uses the
      modern interpretation. Universal propositions do not imply that
      their subject classes have members. That is why <q>All unicorns
      are mammals</q> and <q>No unicorns are mammals</q> can both come
      out true when there are no unicorns.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Conversion, Obversion, and Contraposition (§6.5).</alert>
      These immediate-inference operations transform categorical
      propositions by swapping terms, changing quality, or replacing
      terms with complements. Some transformations preserve truth for
      some forms but not others, so the validity table matters.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>More Complex Translations (§6.6).</alert> Singular claims,
      identity claims, <q>only</q> claims, and related English patterns
      can often be translated into categorical form. The goal is not to
      memorize slogans, but to practice preserving the original claim in
      standard form.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Where We're Headed (§6.7).</alert> Chapter 7 combines
      categorical propositions into syllogisms and uses three-circle
      Venn diagrams to test validity.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch6-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-a-proposition">
        <title>A proposition</title>
        <p>The universal affirmative categorical form: All S are P. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-categorical-logic">
        <title>Categorical logic</title>
        <p>The logic of statements and arguments about categories or classes. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-categorical-proposition">
        <title>Categorical proposition</title>
        <p>A statement that relates two categories, a subject term and a predicate term, in one of the four standard forms. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-contradiction">
        <title>Contradiction</title>
        <p>A relation in which two propositions cannot both be true and cannot both be false. (§6.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-contraposition">
        <title>Contraposition</title>
        <p>An immediate-inference operation that replaces the subject and predicate terms with their complements and swaps their positions. (§6.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-conversion">
        <title>Conversion</title>
        <p>An immediate-inference operation that swaps the subject and predicate terms. (§6.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-e-proposition">
        <title>E proposition</title>
        <p>The universal negative categorical form: No S are P. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-existential-commitment">
        <title>Existential commitment</title>
        <p>A commitment that a category has at least one member. Universal categorical propositions have no existential commitment on the modern interpretation. (§6.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-i-proposition">
        <title>I proposition</title>
        <p>The particular affirmative categorical form: Some S are P. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-immediate-inference">
        <title>Immediate inference</title>
        <p>An inference from one categorical proposition to another. (§6.3, §6.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-modern-interpretation">
        <title>Modern interpretation</title>
        <p>The interpretation of categorical logic on which universal propositions do not imply that their subject classes have members. (§6.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-o-proposition">
        <title>O proposition</title>
        <p>The particular negative categorical form: Some S are not P. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-obversion">
        <title>Obversion</title>
        <p>An immediate-inference operation that changes a proposition's quality and replaces the predicate term with its complement. (§6.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-predicate-term">
        <title>Predicate term</title>
        <p>The category represented by P in a standard form categorical proposition. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-pragmatics">
        <title>Pragmatics</title>
        <p>What a sentence suggests or communicates in context, beyond its strict logical content. (§6.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-quality">
        <title>Quality</title>
        <p>Whether a categorical proposition is affirmative or negative. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-quantity">
        <title>Quantity</title>
        <p>Whether a categorical proposition is universal or particular. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-semantics">
        <title>Semantics</title>
        <p>The strict meaning or truth-conditions of a sentence, as opposed to what it may suggest in context. (§6.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-singular-statement">
        <title>Singular statement</title>
        <p>A statement about an individual rather than directly about a general category. (§6.6)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-square-of-opposition">
        <title>Square of opposition</title>
        <p>A diagram or classification of logical relations among A, E, I, and O propositions. (§6.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch6-subject-term">
        <title>Subject term</title>
        <p>The category represented by S in a standard form categorical proposition. (§6.1)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch6">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch6-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identifying the Form</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each standard-form proposition, identify whether it
          is A, E, I, or O.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s01-01"><statement><p>All voters are people who can be polled.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s01-02"><statement><p>Some senators are not freshmen.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s01-03"><statement><p>No data centers in this district are exempt from new permit requirements.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s01-04"><statement><p>Some supreme court justices are former federal judges.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s01-05"><statement><p>All immigration cases this year are cases reviewed by the new tribunal.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s01-06"><statement><p>Some bills are not bills passed unanimously.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch6-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Translation into Standard Form</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Translate each English sentence into a single standard-form
          categorical proposition. Identify the form (A, E, I, or O).
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-01"><statement><p>Every senator voted on the bill.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-02"><statement><p>Some immigration enforcement actions are not authorized by warrant.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-03"><statement><p>Not all data center proposals get approved by the county.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-04"><statement><p>No tariffs imposed in 2025 are tariffs that lowered consumer prices.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-05"><statement><p>There are voters who voted for the third-party candidate.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-06"><statement><p>Many Virginia counties have rejected new data center applications.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-07"><statement><p>Spiders aren't insects.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s02-08"><statement><p>It's false that no member of Congress opposed the strikes.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch6-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Drawing the Diagram</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each proposition, describe the two-circle Venn
          diagram that represents it: which area is shaded, or
          which area contains an X. Use the standard area numbering
          (1 = S only; 2 = S-and-P overlap; 3 = P only;
          4 = outside both).
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s03-01"><statement><p>All registered voters are people eligible to vote in this election.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s03-02"><statement><p>No data center applications submitted this year are applications approved without environmental review.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s03-03"><statement><p>Some tariffs are tariffs that have produced retaliatory measures.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s03-04"><statement><p>Some Supreme Court justices are not justices appointed in the last decade.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch6-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Immediate Inferences via Contradiction</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each pair of propositions, decide whether the second
          follows from the first by contradiction. (That is, is the
          second the contradictory of the first, and does the truth
          value of the second follow from the truth value of the
          first?)
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s04-01"><statement><p>Premise: It's not the case that all dumpster fires are bad things. Conclusion: Some dumpster fires are not bad things.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s04-02"><statement><p>Premise: No Joe Rogan fans are mainstream Democrats. Conclusion: It's not the case that some Joe Rogan fans are mainstream Democrats.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s04-03"><statement><p>Premise: All bitcoin maximalists are speculators. Conclusion: Some bitcoin maximalists are speculators.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s04-04"><statement><p>Premise: Some Silicon Valley billionaires are people who should stay in their lane. Conclusion: Some Silicon Valley billionaires are not people who should stay in their lane.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch6-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Conversion, Obversion, Contraposition</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each pair, identify the operation (conversion,
          obversion, or contraposition) and decide whether the
          inference is valid on the modern interpretation.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s05-01"><statement><p>Premise: No school board members are ridiculous clowns. Conclusion: No non-ridiculous-clowns are non-school-board-members.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s05-02"><statement><p>Premise: Some logic smarties are philosophy cool kids. Conclusion: Some philosophy cool kids are logic smarties.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s05-03"><statement><p>Premise: All crayons are non-toxic things. Conclusion: No crayons are toxic things.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s05-04"><statement><p>Premise: Some anti-vaxxers are not conspiracy theorists. Conclusion: Some conspiracy theorists are not anti-vaxxers.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s05-05"><statement><p>Premise: Some Kyrie Irving fans are not Dallas Mavericks fans. Conclusion: Some Kyrie Irving fans are non-Dallas-Mavericks-fans.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s05-06"><statement><p>Premise: All registered voters are people on the rolls. Conclusion: All non-people-on-the-rolls are non-registered-voters.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch6-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Complex Translations</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Translate each sentence into one or more standard-form
          categorical propositions. For identity claims, give both
          directions.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-01"><statement><p>Today is Monday.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-02"><statement><p>Donald Trump is the 47th President of the United States.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-03"><statement><p>Only registered voters can vote in this election.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-04"><statement><p>Trump was nominated for a Nobel Peace Prize.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-05"><statement><p>Only Trump supporters are true Americans.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-06"><statement><p>It's false that only Republican die-hards voted for Trump.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-07"><statement><p>Hillary Clinton should have been President of the United States.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch6-s06-08"><statement><p>None but registered voters can vote in this election.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
